\begin_layout Standard
The Southern Ocean holds the largest circumpolar marginal ice zone (MIZ)
 in the world ocean 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 408"
key "weeksSeaIce2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The definition of the MIZ depends on the properties that are of interest
 in each specific study and also on the polar hemisphere.
 Brief list of definition, expanded later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Antarctic, the MIZ is a characteristic of the advancing edge, since
 during this phase sea ice progresses northwards and expands zonally due
 to the increase in ocean surface towards the equator.
 Hence, the MIZ can be depicted as a band of young ice that is continuously
 affected by air-sea interactions, in the form of heat exchanges, wind and
 current drag, and wave action.
 Every latitude of the Southern Ocean will have a period of time in which
 it can be classified as MIZ
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first two mechanisms are at play everywhere in the sea ice.
 They are however dampened because of the consolidated ice conditions and
 the presence of snow that isolates the thinner ice from the atmosphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This feature is found in the Arctic only in the Bering Sea and in the Greenland
 and Norwegian Seas 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wadhamsIceOcean2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, the circumpolar, unbounded features of the Antarctic MIZ makes
 more difficult to aggregate in a Southern Hemisphere view, similarly to
 what happens to trends in sea-ice extent.
 The aggregation masks a large regional variability, and hence it is difficult
 to derive overall significant signals
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
add references
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This regional contrast is likely to be exacerbated in the MIZ, due to its
 naturally divergent features and the increased interaction with the Antarctic
 Circumpolar Current during the advancement phase.
 During the retreat, conditions are more similar to the Arctic: the progressive
 melting and the breaking of ice floes increase the effectiveness of the
 boundary layer processes, which rearrange the pack ice into open drift
 conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sea-ice concentration (SIC), the fraction of ice-covered water, is measured
 at the Earth observation scale through the use of satellites equipped with
 passive microwaves (PM) sensors.
 Operationally, the MIZ is defined as that region of the sea ice where SIC
 is comprised between 15 and 80% 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "comisoConcentrationGradientsGrowth1984,meierComparisonSeaiceExtent2008,strongArcticMarginalIce2013,stroeveMappingAssessingVariability2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This definition is tightly linked to the SIC retrieval from satellite radiometr
y, since the limit of 15% is considered to be a viable rule-of-thumb to
 overcome the uncertainties in the methodology.
 Within this range, sea ice is assumed to be in open pack ice conditions,
 with higher chances of drifting ice and the penetration of gravity waves
 due to the floes being smaller than the wave length 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "squireOceanWaveInteractions2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This definition is operationally viable at the monthly scale in the Antarctic.
 Assuming that the sea-ice edge is traversing a region of open ocean in
 one month, this area is likely to be classified as MIZ, since it will have
 an expected SIC equal to 50%.
 This definition is therefore indicative more of the seasonal ice zone and
 the transition between new and young ice, rather than a measure of the
 MIZ, in which ocean and atmospheric processes are determinant in shaping
 the dynamics of sea ice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "stroeveMappingAssessingVariability2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 found large differences in estimating the MIZ extent using different algorithms.
 BT more consolidated pack ice than NT
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assumption is that the PM-derived concentration contains information
 on the sea-ice type, which has demonstrated skills in the Arctic, where
 the correspondence between ice cover and ice type allows to discriminate
 first year (seasonal) ice from multi-year ice.
 This is less relevant in the Antarctic, where the vast majority of sea
 ice is seasonal.
 Antarctic sea ice cannot thus be decomposed in further categories.
 Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) data are the most viable alternative, but
 they are rare and mostly available routinely around the Antarctic Peninsula
 and in the Ross Sea regions
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
references
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The change in pixel concentration, however small, holds some consistent
 measure of change in ice character.
 The interest here is not whether the retrieval of brightness temperature
 is effectively measuring the concentration of ice-free versus ice-covered
 ocean, but rather if the relative change in this proxy is representative
 of a physical variation in sea ice conditions.
 This is the main concept of the method proposed here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Introduce the concept of predictability of ice conditions for forecasting,
 operational activities and also as a diagnostic to evaluate climate model
 capabilities to simulate the adequate conditions for ecosystem and biogeochemis
try studies.
