Statistical analysis
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Statistical-analysis"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The methodology treats the variability of remote-sensed SIC as if it was
 noise, a perturbation around an expected value.
 SIC is expressed as the fraction between 0 and 1 in all computations and
 figures.
 Regions of closed pack ice, or of ice-free ocean outside the seasonal ice
 zone are more likely to experience small variations around a long-term
 mean value of the SIC (close to 1 in the former case and to 0 in the latter).
 Persistent conditions of multi-year ice and permanently ice-free ocean
 will have less noise, hence a negligible dispersion around the climatological
 mean.
 The standard deviation of the daily SIC anomaly with respect to a chosen
 reference value can thus be used to measure the degree of variance in sea-ice
 conditions experienced by a certain pixel over a month.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The daily SIC anomaly for each pixel is computed by subtracting the daily
 SIC from the monthly climatology 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{i}^{m}=C_{i}^{m}-\overline{C}^{n},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the index 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 runs over the number of days in month 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,\dots,12$
\end_inset

 indicates the month of the year.
 The index 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 runs over the total number of months in the time series (e.g.
 396 for NOAA/NSIDC CDR).
 The reason for choosing the monthly climatology as the reference value
 is further explained below.
 Since the variable SIC is constrained between 0 and 1, so is the anomaly.
 The standard deviation of the daily anomaly is then computed for each month,
 to measure the spread around the climatological SIC monthly mean as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{SIA}^{m}=\sqrt{\frac{1}{N-1}\sum_{i=1}^{N}\left(a_{i}^{m}\right)^{2}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the total number of days in the month.
 The standard deviation is effectively a sum of squares, since the mean
 of the anomalies is null.
 The climatological monthly standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\overline{\sigma}_{SIA}^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 has also been computed by pooling together all the daily anomalies from
 the same month in different years.
 The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{SIA}^{m}$
\end_inset

, hereinafter referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the indicator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, describes a left bounded distribution, where the value 0 indicates lack
 of SIC variability over the month and the maximum expected value is 0.5.
 The exclusion of the zeroes will return an unbiased distribution of SIC
 variability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should be noted that this analysis does not deliberately discriminate
 between a point that is experiencing a seasonal transition of the MIZ band
 during sea-ice advance or a persistence of short-term variable SIC conditions
 more typically ascribed to the ice edge.
 This is the main reason for using the daily anomaly against the monthly
 climatology instead of the daily climatology (based on daily values or
 daily running means over a weekly to monthly time window).
 The use of a filtered background climatology with a window shorter than
 a month does include the smooth daily transition during the advance and
 retreat phase.
 It still retains some features but reduces the variance of the signal due
 to the meridional advancement, which is a fundamental characteristics of
 the MIZ.
 Since the anomaly is computed roughly over the same number of days for
 each pixel (excluding the random missing data), it is more likely that
 a rapid transition between new, young and first-year ice would result in
 an overall lower value of the monthly indicator, nevertheless recording
 the information that this region of the ocean has been partly interested
 by changes in SIC.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability of an ocean region being affected by MIZ conditions during
 a given month has been computed using the empirical exceedance (which is
 equivalent to 1 - CDF, the cumulative density function, when the function
 is known):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
EP=1-\frac{r}{N}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the rank of the sorted series of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{SIA}^{m}$
\end_inset

 values.
 Given a certain threshold of the indicator that corresponds to MIZ conditions,
 this function gives an estimate of the probability to exceed that value.
\end_layout

