\begin_layout Section
Discussion and conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
La regione marginale in Antartico e' caratterizzata da variabilita' di tipologia
 di ghiaccio, che in qualche maniera viene registrato dalle variazioni di
 concentrazione.
 The conventional method uses a concentration threshold method to identify
 regions of sea-ice cover between 15 and 80%.
 Due to the seasonal advancement and retreat of sea ice, the use of SIC
 monthly means allow to record some variability, which is then reflected
 in the overall count of pixels that can be attributed to be part of the
 MIZ 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "strongArcticMarginalIce2013,stroeveMappingAssessingVariability2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, absolute thresholds do not tell the whole story of the MIZ seasonal
 cycle, and especially they do not reflect a direct measure of variability,
 which is the ultimate feature of the MIZ.
 The proposed method allows to identify regions of higher variability and
 to quantify the climatological relative intensity.
 It gives a quantitative measure of the probability to exceed a given level
 of variation in SIC, which is obtained by computing an indicator: the standard
 deviation of the daily anomaly on a monthly basis.
 This indicator can be translated into maps of exceedance probability, hence
 giving a quantitative description of the MIZ characteristics, beyond a
 more conventional classification mask.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method does not require subjective ranges, because the separation between
 pixels of low and high variability is obtained through a distributional
 analysis of the indicator values, which reveals a bimodal pattern.
 A threshold is nevertheless necessary, to distinguish regions of low variabilit
y that are more typical of the inner pack regions.
 The percentage probability of exceeding a given threshold depends on the
 chosen value of the indicator, but it does not modify the relative pattern
 between the regions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The use of a SIC threshold for the MIZ definition leads to a misestimation
 of the sea-ice area that can be affected by variable conditions and different
 ice types in the various seasons.
 TO BE REPHRASED BECAUSE IT
\begin_inset Quotes brd
\end_inset

S MORE NUANCED: In terms of the seasonal climatology, the MIZ area obtained
 through the use of a fixed threshold is underestimated in winter, and far
 below the summer area.
 This may seem paradoxical, because the region classified as MIZ cannot
 be larger than the sea-ice extent.
 This is an artefact of the use of climatological means and the 15% baseline,
 which skews the distribution towards the low values, disregarding the natural
 large variability of sea ice.
 It is thus not surprising that identification of the ice edge is not carried
 out during summertime, because of the fragmentation of the ice surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The use of daily of anomalies computed against the climatological monthly
 mean is justified by: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
calcolare l'anomalia giornaliera sulla media mensile climatologica e' la
 misura che serve.
 Lo scopo e' identificare regioni che sono influenzate 1) da variazioni
 interannuali (e qui si dovrebbe usare l'anomalia rispetto alla climatologia
 daily o weekly) ma anche 2) dalla transizione stagionale del ghiaccio (il
 progressivo congelamento) e 3) che hanno variabilita' dentro al mese (il
 ghiaccio e' piu' o meno compatto ma oscilla).
 Tutte questi tre criteri sono tipici della zona marginale.
 Il punto 2) e' tipico ovunque, e quindi mi genera il rumore stagionale
 di fondo che questo indicatore e' in grado di misurare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is independent of the algorithm and sensors, and less sensitive to the
 uncertainties of the brightness temperature retrieval.
 As long as each product is consistent and not affected by intrinsic biases,
 the proposed analysis will map relative differences between ice types,
 even if the specific ice type cannot be classified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These results have several applications.
 From an operational view point, these maps can be used to plan scientific
 and logistical activities in seasonally ice-covered Southern Ocean waters.
 This method should not be used to measure the extent of pack ice conditions,
 because multi-year ice is not counted due to the reduced inter-annual variabili
ty.
 The MIZ area could however be removed from the SIC-based sea-ice extent,
 to obtain an adjusted estimate that takes into account the regions of high
 variability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to its construction, the method should be mostly applied in climatological
 or medium to long-term investigations of ice variability.
 It may also be used in an operational context, for instance comparing each
 daily anomaly against the long term distribution of anomalies in a particular
 region.
 This has not however been verified in this analysis and would deserve dedicated
 work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the possibility to see patterns of intensity within the region
 classified as MIZ, would allow to identify further linkages with the atmospheri
c boundary layer, as for instance the role played by polar cyclones in shaping
 the character of Antarctic sea ice.
\end_layout

